{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012MDbDDNZCumK4iyE6xWtRb","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 9-2: State schema migration for multi-stack\n     2→\n     3→## Status: backlog\n     4→\n     5→## Story\n     6→\n     7→As a developer upgrading codeharness,\n     8→I want my existing state file to auto-migrate to the new multi-stack format,\n     9→So that I don't have to re-initialize.\n    10→\n    11→## Acceptance Criteria\n    12→\n    13→- [ ] AC1: Given an old state file with `stack: 'nodejs'`, when `readState()` is called, then `state.stacks` is `['nodejs']` and `state.stack` is `'nodejs'` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    14→- [ ] AC2: Given a new state file with `stacks: ['nodejs', 'rust']`, when `readState()` is called, then `state.stacks` is `['nodejs', 'rust']` and `state.stack` is `'nodejs'` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    15→- [ ] AC3: Given a state file with neither `stack` nor `stacks`, when `readState()` is called, then `state.stacks` is `[]` and `state.stack` is `null` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    16→- [ ] AC4: Given state is written via `writeState()`, when the file is inspected, then it contains both `stacks: ['nodejs', 'rust']` AND `stack: 'nodejs'` for backward compat <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    17→\n    18→## Technical Notes\n    19→\n    20→### Changes to `src/lib/state.ts`\n    21→\n    22→The `HarnessState` interface (L7-41) needs:\n    23→\n    24→1. **New field:** `stacks: string[]` — the canonical multi-stack field.\n    25→2. **Keep field:** `stack: string | null` — deprecated, kept for backward compat. Always equals `stacks[0] ?? null`.\n    26→\n    27→### Migration logic in `readState()`\n    28→\n    29→In the existing `readState()` function, add migration after parsing the YAML frontmatter:\n    30→\n    31→```\n    32→if state has `stacks` array → use it, set `stack = stacks[0] ?? null`\n    33→else if state has `stack` string → convert: `stacks = [stack]`, keep `stack` as-is\n    34→else → `stacks = []`, `stack = null`\n    35→```\n    36→\n    37→### Write logic in `writeState()`\n    38→\n    39→Always write both fields:\n    40→- `stacks: ['nodejs', 'rust']`\n    41→- `stack: 'nodejs'` (= `stacks[0] ?? null`)\n    42→\n    43→This ensures old versions of codeharness reading the state file still see a valid `stack` field.\n    44→\n    45→### Update `getDefaultState()`\n    46→\n    47→Accept `stacks: string[]` parameter instead of `stack: string | null`. Set both `stacks` and `stack` (compat) on the default state object.\n    48→\n    49→### Update `src/modules/infra/types.ts`\n    50→\n    51→The `InitResult` interface (L65, L77) has `stack: string | null`. Add `stacks: string[]` alongside it. Keep `stack` as `stacks[0] ?? null` for any consumers that read it.\n    52→\n    53→### Test file\n    54→\n    55→Create/update `src/lib/__tests__/state.test.ts`:\n    56→- Old format migration: `{ stack: 'nodejs' }` → `stacks: ['nodejs']`\n    57→- New format read: `{ stacks: ['nodejs', 'rust'] }` → both fields correct\n    58→- Empty state: neither field → `stacks: []`, `stack: null`\n    59→- Write round-trip: write multi-stack, read back, verify both fields present\n    60→\n    61→## Files to Change\n    62→\n    63→- `src/lib/state.ts` — Add `stacks: string[]` to `HarnessState` (L7-41), add migration logic in `readState()`, update `writeState()` to always write both fields, update `getDefaultState()`\n    64→- `src/modules/infra/types.ts` — Add `stacks: string[]` to `InitResult` (L65, L77), keep `stack` as compat alias\n    65→- `src/lib/__tests__/state.test.ts` — Add migration tests (old format, new format, empty, round-trip)\n    66→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01EPZD8GcmYWyL2DU72ZXXeA","session_id":"90f5ac9b-34a6-4398-bbd9-dd5bc4930bef","uuid":"e9ce0c8d-f6ed-4a89-aeee-67242b1a5a26","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:23:34.773Z"}
