{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GATsxowjKTFTmnhPqJRdwx","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\n\n**Review complete.** Story 9-2 status set to `verifying`.\n\n**Fixes applied:**\n\n1. **HIGH — init-project.ts did not persist multi-stacks to state file.** `state.stacks` was never set from `detectStacks()` results. Only the single root stack from `getDefaultState(stack)` was written. Fixed by adding `state.stacks = result.stacks` before `writeState()` call at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/modules/infra/init-project.ts` line 125.\n\n2. **MEDIUM — writeState mutated caller's state object.** The backward-compat sync (`state.stack = state.stacks[0]`) modified the input object as a side effect. Fixed by shallow-copying before serialization at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/state.ts` line 131.\n\n3. **MEDIUM — isValidState accepted non-string stacks array elements.** An array like `[42, true]` passed validation. Fixed by adding element type check at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/state.ts` line 213.\n\n4. **MEDIUM — recoverCorruptedState relied on writeState mutation side-effect for stack/stacks consistency.** When `detectStack()` returns `null` but `detectStacks()` finds subdirectory stacks, `stack` stayed `null` while `stacks` had entries. The previous code \"worked\" only because `writeState` mutated the object. Fixed by explicitly syncing `stack` from `stacks[0]` at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/state.ts` line 225.\n\n**Test results:** 3100 tests passing, 0 failures. Coverage: 97.03% overall, all 123 files above 80% floor.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Bugs found and fixed:**\n- HIGH: `init-project.ts` never persisted multi-stacks to state file — only single root stack was written. All `detectStacks()` results were lost on init.\n- MEDIUM: `writeState()` mutated caller's state object via `state.stack = state.stacks[0]` side effect.\n- MEDIUM: `isValidState()` accepted `stacks: [42, true]` as valid — no element type checking.\n- MEDIUM: `recoverCorruptedState()` produced inconsistent `stack: null` / `stacks: ['nodejs']` state, relying on `writeState` mutation to fix it.\n\n**Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW):**\n- `migrateState()` unconditionally casts `raw.stack as StackName` without validating the string is a known stack name. An old state file with `stack: 'go'` would produce `stacks: ['go']` which is not a valid `StackName`. Low risk since only internal state files use this.\n- `recoverCorruptedState()` calls both `detectStack()` and `detectStacks()` — `detectStack()` internally calls `detectStacks()`, so stack detection runs twice. Minor perf waste.\n- Flaky test: `sprint/__tests__/state.test.ts > writeStateAtomic > writes valid JSON` failed once during full suite run but passes in isolation — shared `sprint-state.json` file creates race condition under parallel test execution.\n\n**Coverage gaps:**\n- `init-project.test.ts` has zero assertions on the `stacks` field in state files after init. The fix is covered by unit tests on `state.ts` but no integration-level test verifies `initProject()` writes multi-stack state.\n- No test for `recoverCorruptedState` when root stack is null but subdirectory stacks exist (the scenario fixed in issue #4).\n\n**Architecture concerns:**\n- None significant. The dual-field `stack`/`stacks` pattern is pragmatic for backward compat but will accumulate tech debt if not eventually deprecated.\n\n**Items sent back for re-development:**\n- None. All HIGH and MEDIUM issues fixed."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a2cb39160c35f1bb2 (use SendMessage with to: 'a2cb39160c35f1bb2' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 66976\ntool_uses: 39\nduration_ms: 239657</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"90f5ac9b-34a6-4398-bbd9-dd5bc4930bef","uuid":"1882f4a0-3051-4edf-be0b-62f42d6f6906","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:36:31.289Z","tool_use_result":{"statu