{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_016ZaCRocwfX7iCQ5R5jzDGz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WL7DrxmGLAhZkC47Da34oq","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd /tmp/codeharness-verify-9-2-state-schema-migration-multi-stack && claude --print --max-budget-usd 5 --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"You are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective — using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The src/ directory does not exist. This is intentional — you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading README.md in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story file story.md contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Read it now.\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via docker exec codeharness-verify ...\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n\n### Docker Container\n\n- Container name: codeharness-verify\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: docker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n- Example: docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version\n- Example: docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness init --json\n\nThe container has the following tools installed:\n- codeharness — the project CLI\n- node, npm — Node.js runtime\n- curl, jq — for querying observability endpoints\n\n### Project Type: Node.js CLI\n\nExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n- docker exec codeharness-verify <cli-command> [args]\n- Capture exit codes: docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c '<command>; echo EXIT:\\$?'\n- For Node.js projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.\n\n### Verification Strategy for State Migration\n\nThis story is about internal state functions (readState, writeState, migrateState, getDefaultState, isValidState, recoverCorruptedState). Since these are internal functions, you must verify them through their OBSERVABLE EFFECTS:\n\n- AC1-AC3 (readState migration): Use codeharness init to create a project, then manually edit the state YAML file to test migration scenarios. After editing, run codeharness status --json and check the stacks/stack fields in the output.\n- AC4 (writeState dual-write): After codeharness init, inspect the raw YAML state file for both stack and stacks fields.\n- AC5 (getDefaultState): Run codeharness init in a Node.js project dir and verify the initial state has both fields.\n- AC6 (recoverCorruptedState): Write garbage to the state file and run a codeharness command that reads state — verify it recovers with both fields.\n- AC7 (isValidState): Test that old-format state files (only stack, no stacks) still work when read by codeharness.\n- AC8 (regression): Run codeharness test or npm test inside the container to verify all tests pass.\n\nFor AC8 specifically, if npm test is available in the container, run it. If not, verify by running several codeharness commands that exercise different code paths and confirm they all work correctly.\n\n### Observability Endpoints\n\nQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n\n- VictoriaLogs (logs): http://localhost:9428\n  - Example: curl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&limit=10'\n- VictoriaMetrics (metrics): http://localhost:8428\n  - Example: curl 'http://localhost:8428/api/v1/query?query=up'\n- VictoriaTraces (traces): http://localhost:16686\n  - Example: curl 'http://localhost:16686/api/traces?service=codeharness-verify&limit=10'\n\n## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n\nAfter EACH docker exec command you run, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n\ncurl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n\n- If the response contains one or more log entries, the code path has observability coverage. Note the count in your proof.\n- If the response contains zero log entries, tag it: [OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: verification/9-2-state-schema-migration-multi-stack-proof.md\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n\n## AC N: <description>\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n\\`\\`\\`output\n<actual output>\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**IMPORTANT: Only use bash and output as code fence languages.** Never use bare fences without a language tag.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. ALL commands MUST use docker exec codeharness-verify ... — do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n2. Do NOT attempt to access source code — there is no src/ directory in this workspace.\n3. Report REAL failures — if a feature does not work via the CLI, report that as a verification failure.\n4. Every AC needs functional evidence — reading docs alone is not evidence. You must execute commands and capture output.\n5. [ESCALATE] is ONLY for things that are genuinely impossible to automate — physical hardware, paid external services, human visual judgment. Infrastructure problems are NOT valid escalation reasons.\n6. Never switch to unit-testable verification. If Docker verification does not work, report WHY as a [FAIL].\" 2>&1","description":"Run black-box verifier session for story 9-2","timeout":300000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":444,"cache_read_input_tokens":61015,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":444},"output_tokens":57,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"90f5ac9b-34a6-4398-bbd9-dd5bc4930bef","uuid":"8bda0554-8d33-4e29-a03c-6bf7d02e70b2"}
